## Test Anti-Pattern Audit: `SerializerTests.cs`

**Summary: 4 Critical · 0 High · 2 Medium · 0 Low**

This suite is dominated by **self-referential / tautological assertions** — 4 of 8 tests can never fail regardless of whether the production code is correct. Two additional tests have meaningful but incomplete verification. Only 2 tests (the serialization round-trip and `Money.Parse` round-trip) are genuinely sound.

---

### 🔴 Critical — False Confidence

#### 1. `UpperCase_ToUpper_Works` (line 72–77) — Self-referential assertion

The input `"HELLO"` is **already uppercase**, so `.ToUpper()` is a no-op. The test asserts `input == result` on an identity operation. It would pass even if `ToUpper()` were a stub returning its argument unchanged.

```csharp
// BEFORE — tautological: ToUpper("HELLO") == "HELLO" trivially
var input = "HELLO";
var result = input.ToUpper();
Assert.AreEqual(input, result);

// AFTER — actually tests a transformation
var input = "hello";
var result = input.ToUpper();
Assert.AreEqual("HELLO", result);
```

---

#### 2. `NormalizeName_AlreadyNormalized_NoChange` (line 37–42) — Self-referential assertion

`Normalize()` does `Trim().ToLowerInvariant()`. The input `"alice"` is already trimmed and lowercase — the method is a no-op. This never verifies that normalization actually transforms anything.

```csharp
// BEFORE — "alice" is already normalized, so output == input trivially
var name = "alice";
var result = NameNormalizer.Normalize(name);
Assert.AreEqual(name, result);

// AFTER — test with input that actually needs normalization
[DataRow("  Alice  ", "alice")]
[DataRow("BOB", "bob")]
[DataRow("  charlie ", "charlie")]
[TestMethod]
public void NormalizeName_TrimsAndLowercases(string input, string expected)
{
    var result = NameNormalizer.Normalize(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

---

#### 3. `GetDisplayName_ReturnsFormattedName` (line 56–61) — Self-referential assertion

`GetDisplayName()` returns `Name` verbatim (production code line 10). The test asserts `user.Name == display`, which is asserting a field equals itself through a trivial accessor. Despite the name saying "FormattedName", no formatting is ever verified.

```csharp
// BEFORE — asserts dto.Name == dto.Name through a pass-through method
var display = user.GetDisplayName();
Assert.AreEqual(user.Name, display);

// AFTER — assert against a known expected value; if formatting is
// added later (e.g., "Alice (30)"), the test will correctly fail.
var user = new UserDto { Name = "Alice", Age = 30 };
var display = user.GetDisplayName();
Assert.AreEqual("Alice", display);  // explicit expected value
```

---

#### 4. `MapToDto_MapBack_RoundTrip` (line 45–53) — Tautological round-trip on lossy mapping

The production code reveals this mapping is **lossy**: `ToDto` drops `Id` and `Email`; `ToEntity` drops `Age`. The test asserts the round-trip preserves `Id`, `FullName`, and `Email` — but `backToEntity.Id` will be `0` (not `1`) and `backToEntity.Email` will be `""` (not `"a@b.com"`). This test either **silently fails** (if not actually run) or exposes a fundamental misunderstanding of the mapping contract. Either way, the round-trip pattern is wrong here — the mapping is not invertible.

```csharp
// BEFORE — asserts a lossy round-trip preserves data it actually drops
var dto = Mapper.ToDto(entity);
var backToEntity = Mapper.ToEntity(dto);
Assert.AreEqual(entity.Id, backToEntity.Id);       // 1 != 0
Assert.AreEqual(entity.FullName, backToEntity.FullName); // only one that works
Assert.AreEqual(entity.Email, backToEntity.Email);  // "a@b.com" != ""

// AFTER — test each direction independently against known values
[TestMethod]
public void ToDto_MapsFullNameToName()
{
    var entity = new UserEntity { Id = 1, FullName = "Alice Smith", Email = "a@b.com" };
    var dto = Mapper.ToDto(entity);
    Assert.AreEqual("Alice Smith", dto.Name);
    Assert.AreEqual(0, dto.Age);  // document that Age is not mapped
}

[TestMethod]
public void ToEntity_MapsNameToFullName()
{
    var dto = new UserDto { Name = "Alice Smith", Age = 30 };
    var entity = Mapper.ToEntity(dto);
    Assert.AreEqual("Alice Smith", entity.FullName);
    Assert.AreEqual(0, entity.Id);    // document that Id is not mapped
    Assert.AreEqual("", entity.Email); // document that Email is not mapped
}
```

---

### 🟡 Medium — Incomplete Verification

| # | Test | Issue | Fix |
|---|------|-------|-----|
| 5 | `Clone_ProducesEqualObject` (line 28) | Asserts value equality but never checks **reference inequality** (`AreNotSame`). Clone could return `this` and the test would pass. | Add `Assert.AreNotSame(original, clone);` |
| 6 | `Validate_ValidInput_ReturnsSameInput` (line 64) | Only tests the happy path. No test that invalid input throws `ArgumentException`. Half the contract is unverified. | Add a test: `Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentException>(() => Validator.ValidateEmail("bad"));` |

---

